Republican Strategy for Re-election of Obama
Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to combat election fraud.
However, the Brennan Center is considered the latter a myth, arguing that cases of falsifications in elections in the United States are more rare than deaths from a lightning strike.
In addition, Republican lawyers counted only 300 cases of electoral falsifications in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new trends will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for organizing the U.S. federal election.
That is why most state governments have enacted laws that complicate the registration or voting process since 2009.
This phenomenon gained a new scale after the November 2010 elections, which brought Republicans 675 new seats in 26 states.
As a result, in 2011 alone, 180 bills were passed restricting the right to vote in 41 states.
The new election laws require the voter to present a photo of an identity card and proof of American citizenship.
In addition, these laws reduce the period of early voting, abolish the right to register the voter on the day of the will and take away the right to vote from citizens who have a criminal record.
Until the 2006 election, no U.S. staff required voters to present a photo of an identity card.
Indiana was the first state to introduce such a requirement.
The U.S. Supreme Court confirmed in 2008 the constitutionality of the Indiana law.
The Republican authorities rushed to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have initiated bills requiring voters to present photo cards in 34 states.
It is important to note that unlike Quebec, American citizens do not have such a universal identity card as a health insurance card.
Indeed, 11% of U.S. citizens, that is, 21 million people who have reached the age required to vote, do not have an identity card with a photo issued by the government body of their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a document.
At the same time, the cost of obtaining the required identity card often exceeds a hundred dollars.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over the age of 65 and 20% of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have the required photo ID.
But that's not all.
Students - voters who are considered to vote for Democratic candidates are not allowed in several states to use a photo ID issued by their school.
But the same states allow members of fishing and hunting clubs, who vote mainly for Republicans, to use the certification issued by these clubs to vote.
Until 2004, no state required evidence of U.S. nationality for voting.
For the first time, such a requirement was introduced in Arizona.
Since 2011, more than a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove that they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are obviously intended to restrict the vote of Latin Americans.
It is believed that two-thirds of Latin American voters vote in favor of the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican lawmakers initiated in 2011 laws abolishing voter registration on voting day in eight states.
They also restricted the right of individuals or groups to provide assistance to those who wish to register.
This restriction did not pass without consequences.
For example, during the 2004 elections, the voter registration campaign helped to list some 10 million citizens.
At the same time, the measures taken since 2009 have resulted in a 17 per cent drop in the level of registration of new voters in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers have passed laws in five other states aimed at reducing the period of early voting.
For example, during the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of voters who voted early were African American, although the latter accounted for only 13% of the total number of voters in the state.
The same thing happened to people from Latin America.
Representing only 11% of voters, they accounted for 24% of citizens who voted early.
Unlike whites, which, forming 76% of voters, among those who voted on an early one was only 46%.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters are actively opposed to passing laws restricting voter registration.
Several draft laws were vetoed by the Democratic governors.
The most controversial laws were suspended during the intervention of the United States Attorney General.
This has partially limited the negative effects.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring a photo identification.
However, the new rules that have come into effect will certainly make it difficult to implement the right to suffrage in the 2012 elections.
Democratic critics condemn the bias of the laws that were passed, seeing them as an obvious focus on the impact of the 2012 election in key states.
A 2011 report by the Brennan Center shows that the states that have passed these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes required by the Electoral College to win the presidential election.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes at the electoral system level will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential election.
Only one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
