The Higgs Boson in Detail
Last summer, the report that the scientists may have been able to find the Higgs boson, caused a real hype - and not without reason.
It is believed that this boson explains the mass of all the particles in the universe, not much less.
In addition, this is the last particle whose existence was predicted within the Standard Model - our best model, or in any case, "the least of the imperfect" description of the nature and behavior of matter - but which has not been discovered before.
But physicists are not yet fully sure that we are talking about the Higgs boson.
We know, without a shadow of a doubt, that we are dealing with a really new particle and that it strongly resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, the new data presented this week at one major physical congress in Kyoto seem to confirm this, although some data still lacks certainty.
Let's imagine that we are talking about the Higgs boson, because the chances of a mistake seem minimal, and we'll see what that means.
There is, in this world, one law is absolutely inevitable, saying that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
There is no way to bypass this rule, don't even try too hard, otherwise you hurt yourself.
But although the physics of elementary particles is a rather strange world, it turns out that it also has one law of this nature: the principle of Pauli's exclusion, which postulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time, if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" is, in general terms, in some of their characteristics.
On this basis, physicists divide particles into two categories.
In one corner, we find decent citizens, called fermions, who reasonably obey the Pauli principle.
In the other, bosons, a heinous gang of anarchists who have no respect for anything - at least for this principle, which means that they can be calmed down in the same place at the same time.
According to the website (by the way, absolutely extraordinary) Particle Adventure of the Berkeley Laboratory, these bosons are divided, in turn, into two groups: mesons, which we will not talk about here, and "particles of power," through which the main forces of nature are spread and to which in some ways the Higgs boson is spread.
These very bosons, it should be emphasized, not all such exotic creatures as one might think.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to one incredibly banal boson: a photon, or "light particle," which is the "courier" of electromagnetic force.
In fact, when one particle having an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disrupts" the electromagnetic field in this particular place, roughly like a stone thrown into the pond.
From this "violation" is born an electromagnetic wave (light, or infrared radiation, or ultraviolet light, etc. d.), and this wave is nothing but a photon - and, therefore, one of the bosons of "power carriers."
A more stable field
The same thing is happening with the Higgs boson, with the only difference that in order for this boson to appear, another field, the Higgs field, must be "violated."
However, the Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; in order to excite it, it is necessary to achieve very, very high energies, as if we were talking about a frozen pond, the surface of which could shake only a very large stone.
That's why a huge particle accelerator is needed, like the one that is operated at CERN - the Large Hadron Collider, which is a ring with a diameter of 27 km! to achieve such huge energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is also useful for explaining the ratio between the Higgs boson and mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, interact, others - no: a sheet of paper, for example, will never stay on the refrigerator.
Similarly, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that interact have mass, while others (like a photon, by the way) do not have it.
So, what "can bring" all these studies, asks Ms. Plamonddon?
In science, they are used to test the correctness of the Standard Model (SM), and it also allows physicists to find a discrepancy between observations and SM predictions.
In addition, some of them are eager to find such a discrepancy, that such a discrepancy is revealed. To. The slightest discrepancy can open the door to "new physics" and shut up some of the Model holes.
The latter, I must say, still has significant flaws, without offering any explanation for gravity (Oh!) or for dark matter, which forms about 80% of the universe (ch-ch!).
But so far in CERN have not found such discrepancies.
The consequences
It is more difficult to predict the average person's daily life, but it would be a mistake to assume that it is not.
Look: in the early 60s, the pioneers of laser research in Bell's laboratories could not even have imagined what revolution their work would cause.
They foresaw their applications in science, but nothing more.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Labs, where a laser was invented in 1960, and which itself developed the first continuous laser (previously pulsed) in 1962, said that the laser was originally considered rather as a "laboratory gadget."
Let's get it...
And in addition, the application can be found for the tools that accompany the study.
For example, the same Williard Boyle, during his optical research in 1969, developed a small light sensor.
This sensor, although it was not its original purpose, now serves as an "eye" for all the digital cameras in the world and earned the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This, of course, does not mean that the work of the Great Hadron Collider will necessarily change our lives, but it only shows, in fact, that everything can be.
