Pay and Sell Without Bank Help - With Bitcoin
The exact opposite of the current money exchange, based on central banks, numbered transactions between the receiving parties with commission fees for their processing.
In addition, as often happens with these technologies, there is a political vision: the belief that the current monetary system, consisting of banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (pseudus), is simultaneously a virtual currency (buttoned to dollars, euros ...) and a protected exchange protocol by type BitTorrent, which allows you to exchange files between participants of the same level.
About 200,000 transactions have already been registered with 15,000 computers on the network.
Several thousand sites accept bitcoins for donations or as a means of payment.
The Bitcoin exchange rate, peaking at $30 ($23) in June 2011, fell five months later to $2 before returning to about ten dollars today (the rates are listed on bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing special in comparison with the world exchange of real money or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) in its report on the virtual currency, published in October, became interested in this system.
He describes bitcoin as "the most successful virtual currency," "competing with the dollar or euro" and "like conventional currencies."
Bitcoin is different from other types of virtual currencies, like the "loans" used to promote in a video game that is earned during the game or that can be bought (and sometimes exchanged).
The social network Facebook has also developed a similar system.
But the exchange operations always monitor and handle any central authority.
In Bitcoin, all the nodes of the network are simultaneously holders of the ledgers, auditors, currency issuers, dummy and sellers.
How does this network function?
Each transaction between two users actually happens between two email addresses, like an email.
Only for each new payment, the user can choose a different address, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information relating to this transaction is signed electronically, using a double-key encryption system.
The network can also verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is possible to verify that the bitcoins used in the deal do exist in a public account book sent out across the network.
The key step is to register a new transaction in this book.
It goes through the solution of a mathematical problem sent to computers, which, as if a temporary central bank, receives the privilege of adding this new line.
We are talking about the phase of the hashage of the file, that is, the conversion of a large file to a digital signature, short and unique.
Computers "take" a new transaction and add a number to it before "hashing" all together.
The goal is to find a number that will give a unique digital signature (many zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, other nodes are easy to verify that it is correct.
The transaction in this way turns out to be unrorzingly connected to the chain of all other transactions; any modification will change the digital signature.
If, in order to deceive the user very quickly (less than ten minutes) would like to pay twice on the same topic with the same money, only one of these two transactions would be confirmed by the network - and the other would remain unconfirmed, since they have different electronic signatures.
The computer that solved the problem gets 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, the reward is regularly shared in half, probably by the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible to one hundred million, which leaves the reserve.
The complexity of the task also increases with increasing computing power.
The life of the network has already experienced ups and downs.
The sites providing Bitcoin services were attacked and bitcoins were stolen from reserves.
"The defect used does not apply to the protocol itself," says Pierre Nuaza, who recently launched Paymium, a company that makes payments with real money using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reported on the possibility of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But the cash also has that shortcoming.
Major players, such as Wikipedia, refuse to accept donations of this kind.
Others, such as the WordPress blogging platform, allow them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the counting book and found that almost 80% of bitcoins are not in circulation.
"Giant sales" were announced in November.
"Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged," rejoices Jon Holmqvist, who works at Coinabul, which is engaged in converting bitcoin into gold.
Pierre Nuaza, another author of the manual on this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as an operating network.
Its system, Paytunia, is the equivalent of a credit card (in real money) or contactless payment via a mobile phone, but it uses Bitcoin to verify transactions, which is cheaper.
The owner controls his personal data better and can thus be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement for entrepreneurs who do not need to install new devices or software.
It is enough only to tell the address that can be "photographed and recognized" by the phone, says Pierre Nuaza, assuring that he has thousands of users.
There is a general tendency to revise hierarchical systems in favor of more horizontal systems.
"Before Bitcoin is approved, it will take some time, but 2013 may be a turning point," he predicts.
The ECB in its report suggests, by the way, to reconsider the various risks considered to be increased today, if this system succeeds.
