Poland and the space.
Last week, at a meeting of European Space Agency's ministers, Poland was adopted by the twentieth member of the European Space Agency as the second country from the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on September 12, 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and took an active part in several of the agency's projects over the following years.
But Poland began the path to space much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish enthusiasts were engaged in flights to space, but this was not always met with understanding.
Let me remind you, for example, of lectures A. Sternfeld, who on December 6, 1933 represented at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory ideas from his innovative work "Introduction to Cosmonautics."
Ideas of a young engineer (1905) left the audience indifferent, after several years Sternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadom was interested in his work.
In 1934, in France, Sternfeld won the Robert Esno-Peltri and Andre Luis Hirsch Award for "Introduction to Cosmos."
Dr. Jan Gadom (1899-1966), mentioned above, later became a great propagandist of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He has published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and has written a number of books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadom became a well-known world propagandist of cosmonautics, and his contribution was appreciated, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the far side of the moon was named in his honor.
Already in 1925 in Poland was built a railway rail, equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of this idea remained unknown, as well as the details of the project.
It is not even clear that a rocket was to be used for overclocking or braking the cart.
Information about this trunk is known only from the press of that era.
In 1933, Polish artillery began to think about rocket arrows.
The research was carried out by the Armament Engineering Section in cooperation with professors Mechislav Wolfke and Gustav Mokzytsky.
From the surviving materials it is clear that the research has reached the stage of practical tests.
But with the arrival of the German troops, the work was interrupted.
In 1937, the idea of a photovoltaic fighter rocket, which was proposed by the engineer Rogozinsky, appeared in a specialized seal, and the next year the work "Air Torpedo rocket and an aircraft bomb" of the author Levey-Kzhivoblotsky.
Both projects were developed for the military use of rocket engines.
Before the war, all the projects of the military use of missile technology were carried out by the Interim Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), which coordinated all the work.
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of its work, the work ended due to the outbreak of the war.
The next scientific work on cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, the society is mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the journal "Problems," which publishes four voluminous articles on astronautics.
One of them is Professor M. Subotovich proposed to organize a society that will deal with space exploration.
At that time, the projects of artificial satellites were already gaining momentum, and it was clear that space research was a promising industry.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Society of Astronautics (POA) tried to join the international federation of astronautics (founded in 1951), and in the autumn the POA became its full member.
And the following year, the first chairman of the POA Kazimezh Zarankevich (1902-1959) became Deputy Chairman of the International Federation of Astronautics.
In this position, he remained until his death, which occurred in 1959.
Since 1956, the POA has made a significant contribution to the development of a very successful meteorological missile RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to perform scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on 10 October 1958.
The rocket, capable of overcoming the distance of 1800 m, was about 80 cm long, and its weight was less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version of the RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959, a two-stage RM-2 missile was tested at the Bledov wasteland.
This rocket was about 1.4 m long, and its weight was about 11.5 kg.
The next version of the rocket was already able to engage in real scientific work - the RM-34 missile could overcome 14.5 km, and its task was to monitor the high-altitude wind.
But in 1962, further development was suspended.
The heir to the first RM missiles was the Meteor-1 missile, developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was conceived as a two-stage, its total length was 510 cm, and the initial weight - 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed (designated as Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed in the size of the chamber for scientific equipment.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space of 0.4 liters, Meteor-1V - 0.34 liters, and Meteor-1C - 0.62L.
The maximum flight range of all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Aviation Institute, and its first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket with a starting weight of 380 kg was capable of delivering a payload weighing 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
Then versions of Meteor-2N and Meteor-3 were built.
It is also worth mentioning the entry of Poland into the COSPAR (Committee on Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of the national committee of COSPAR two years later.
In addition, as part of the Intercosmos program, Poland participated in the exploration of outer space on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslav Germashevsky became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
