Sabo: "The Germans must play a more important role"
Germany abstained from the vote on the recognition of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on relations between the United States and Europe, in doing so, Berlin is balancing on a narrow diplomatic track.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany first made it clear that it would vote against the Palestinian application for observer status with the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained in the vote.
Why? Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support the Israeli actions in Gaza.
Germany must now be cautious about its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I believe that it does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - not being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained from voting on the introduction of a no-go zone for flights.
NATO eventually held this proposal.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on complex international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
The fact is that it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, namely, it moves from the policy, which, so to speak, was ruled by the United States, to the German foreign policy itself.
In addition, the situation is complicated by the fact that Europeans do not have a coordinated unified policy.
Thus, the Germans are again between the two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe that so far they are only groping their role, but are on the way to a "more normal" foreign policy.
The foreign policy that France or Britain conducts.
What exactly does "normal" foreign policy mean from the German point of view?
It is a willingness to take a position in its national interest, independent of the position of the United States or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy depends on economic policy, that is, on exports and ties with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are very different from that of other major states, and Germany must therefore defend its interests.
Did these economic interests affect the position in the Middle East conflict and the vote in the UN?
First, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, particularly in the Gulf states.
It must therefore be cautious in order not to offend the public and the elites in the Arab countries.
In any case, it plays a role.
But I wouldn't give it too much of that, it's not a completely one-sided connection.
But in any case, this plays an important role in the calculations of the Germans.
Did Germany have harmed its relations with the United States, refraining from making important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I am sure that in Europe and even in the United States, the understanding of the German position prevails.
So I don't think it was as dramatic a breakdown as it did in the Libyan question.
Germany may even gain some respect.
After all, this signals that it should be taken seriously as a player in the international arena and that her interests should be taken into account.
There are different views on the Palestinian initiative in Europe.
The United States, on the contrary, clearly spoke in favor of the veto.
Is there a divergence of opinions between the US and many European countries?
Because of American domestic policy, such differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama government deep down has a sufficient understanding of the European position.
But due to the local political situation, the government, of course, cannot openly take such a position.
I believe that the significant differences of opinion are not as significant as it always seems.
If you consider the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is not at all excited about Netanyahu's policies.
Is it easy for Germany to combine its close ties with Israel and the United States on the one hand and the position of a crucial partner in the EU on the other?
I think that's what makes the situation so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be somewhat easier for the Germans if there were a single, consistent European policy, but now it is not.
They are therefore unable to act within a broader approach and are forced to act instead, based only on their own vision of the situation.
That's what they do with the euro.
I think that in the future Germany will take the lead in developing a common European position.
It is clear that this is not easy for Germany, at least because of ties with Israel.
This topic has always been tickling.
But I think it's clear to the Germans that they should play a more independent role.
If Germany sees itself as an important international player - will it really take the lead?
Or is the leading role still hard for Germany?
Germany is not yet accustomed to this, it is still unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult to play a significant role.
Consider, for example, the euro crisis - every time Germany takes on an important role, a variety of anti-German feelings are manifested.
The Germans don't just deal with it.
In fact, this is an old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much worse situation than the United States.
It should take into account a variety of neighbors and opinions, and this is not easy.
So, the influence of the US in European policy is constantly weakening, but at the moment the EU does not fill this vacuum, who remains?
The Germans will have to play a bigger role.
Even if you don't like it, unpleasantly or increases your dislike for you - that's life!
Stephen Szabo is the deputy director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institute in which academics and political scientists from Europe and North America jointly explore the problems of the transatlantic community.
In addition, Szabo is a member of the German Marshall Fund, in which he specializes in German politics, U.S. foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
