Bradley Manning did not complain of ill-treatment, the accusation.
The prosecutors are trying to refute Bradley Manning's statements about poor conditions of detention.
During the hearing, increased attention was paid to Manning's stay in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense requires that the case be closed on the grounds that Manning's terms of detention were brutal.
A U.S. Army is accused of kidnapping several thousand secret documents.
On Friday, the prosecution tried to prove that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of classified material in U.S. history, did not take advantage of many opportunities to file a complaint about ill-treatment, which he said he had to postpone while in a military prison.
During a cross-examination at a pre-trial hearing in Fort Meade, Maryland, military prosecutor Major Ashden Fein said that records of Manning's weekly visits by representatives of the prison administration for nine months of his detention in Quanticko, Virginia, did not contain complaints of ill-treatment.
Cross-examination as part of the defence's motion to terminate the Manning case on the grounds that the terms of his detention were brutal and by themselves a sufficient punishment were carried out the day after Manning stated that while he was in custody, he intended to commit suicide.
A military intelligence analyst arrested in June 2010 is accused of kidnapping several thousand classified documents while serving in Iraq.
These materials were subsequently published on the Internet on the WikiLeaks website.
The WikiLeaks did not confirm that the source of the information was Manning.
During a hearing on Friday, Fein's prosecutor, along with Manning, reviewed reports that were filled out after Manning's visits by administration officials during his time in Kvantico prison, where he was on strict detention from July 2010 to April 2011.
During the visits, the prison officers asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When prosecutor Fein asked the reports on Friday, Manning admitted that he was assessing his treatment by the prison administration as "excellent," and the general conditions of detention as "very professionally organized."
The reports did not contain complaints of ill-treatment, despite the fact that Manning was directly asked about the conditions of his detention, Fein said.
