My crisis of national self-determination is a story of an American of Mexican descent.
According to the author, many Mexicans were forced to leave Mexico because of the lack of opportunities to realize themselves.
Mexicans tend to blame those who left because they remind the people of the country about difficult times.
Ruben Navarette believes that Mexicans of American origin are torn between two cultures.
During a recent trip to Mexico City, I walked down the corridor for arrivals, approached the border control zone and froze on the spot.
The signs pointed to two queues: one for Mexicanos (Mexicans), the second for Extranjeros (foreigners).
I stood in front of them for a few seconds, not knowing where to go.
I grew up in central California and I've been called a Mexican all my life.
It's just a conditional name, just like my friends in Boston call themselves Irish, and friends from New York consider themselves Italian.
Later I stopped at the complex design of "American of Mexican descent."
But I was here in Mexico.
Here, in my grandfather's homeland, there was no need for conditional names or complex structures.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish well enough to ask questions or answer them.
But my vocabulary is poorer than my native speakers, and I can't get rid of the American accent.
That's why I got my American passport and I'm in line for Extranjeros.
I remembered this story a few days ago, when Mexican newly elected President Enrique Pena Nieto visited the White House and met with President Obama.
On the agenda were the usual issues for the meetings of the presidents of these countries: immigration, drugs and trade.
President Penha Nieto was willing to talk about the rise of the Mexican economy, which would allow the Mexicans to stay in Mexico with the same success, instead of moving to the United States.
He wants to conclude a partnership agreement with the United States and Canada and create a North American trade bloc like the European Union.
In addition, President Pena Nieto promised to continue the war against drug cartels in Mexico, but no concrete proposals were made.
For Mexico, relations with the United States are a difficult and executed old question.
Most Americans never thought that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and at gunpoint forced its leaders to abandon half of its territory.
But the Mexicans think for centuries, not minutes, and see reminders of those events in everything.
Therefore, it is necessary only to some US statesman to be told at least a word of criticism towards Mexico, in the press and among the elite of Mexican society there are immediately complaints that the Americans encroach on the sovereignty of their neighbors.
And the descendants of Montezuma are filled with belligerence.
At the same time, Mexico's relations with more than 35 million Mexican Americans living in the United States are the most difficult.
You want to talk about resentments?
They're enough.
In Mexico, there are winners and losers, people who find opportunities in this country, and those for whom there are no such opportunities.
In Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio, so many people of Mexican origin are for only one reason: at some point in their family history, someone - a father or grandfather - did not have the opportunity to realize himself in Mexico and was forced to go north.
Most often they were Mexicans of a certain type - swarthy, poorly educated, from poor peasant families.
We are their descendants, and we remember it.
They see it differently in Mexico.
Today, our life is the embodiment of the American dream, we studied in good schools and got a good job, but we do not forget that even this dream is American, not Mexican.
Our national self-determination is confusing and unclear, but we know which country to consider our own.
United States of America.
In addition, we know that most of the representatives of the Mexican elite and the ruling class do not like us.
We answer them the same.
They see us as a reminder of humiliating defeats and treat us as second-class people as untrue Mexicans.
We don't speak well in Spanish, and our ties to Mexico are not strong enough.
Our very existence is due to their failures.
If our ancestors had succeeded in Mexico, they wouldn't have left.
We would not be behind the silk curtain, finding a full life in the United States, but losing spiritual ties.
My wife was born in Guadalajara and moved to the United States as a child, and this reminds me that there are certain frictions between real Mexicans and Mexican-Americans - Mexicans understand their national identity, and Americans of Mexican descent are hurting.
She is a U.S. citizen and believes that it belongs to both of these countries.
At the same time, many of my acquaintances of Mexican origin do not feel belonging to any of them.
We listen to the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but we love Bruce Springsteen.
Getting the best from two worlds, you inevitably lose root.
We are Americans in Mexico.
In the United States, we are called Mexicans.
Now, as I found out during my trip, as if our relationship was not confusing enough, some Mexican leaders and intellectuals want to restore relations with the diaspora.
They want Mexican-Americans to work as Mexican ambassadors and represent her interests in the United States.
We could tell our American friends about what a beautiful country it is and how great it is to visit it, and we could convince political leaders to strengthen ties with Mexico.
Yeah, of course you are.
It's not gonna work.
Too much resentment in the past.
And given the gap between the rich and the poor, the rampant corruption and drug trafficking, many of us do not consider this country so beautiful.
Sorry, but deal with it yourself, Amigos.
And that's fair.
If some Mexicans still can't forgive the United States, as they did to Mexico a century and a half ago, they will have to accept the fact that some Americans of Mexican origin are still offended for how recently in Mexico treated their relatives.
I------
We probably have more in common than I thought.
Old Battles in the New Middle East
The ceasefire agreement between Israel and the Hamas group could be a fragile foundation for further peace
Is lasting peace possible between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East?
The next round of bloodshed pushes us to conclude that such hopes are futility.
Sounds familiar, meaningless controversy over who first started; many buildings have been turned into ruins; more than 140 Palestinians have been killed, most civilians, and six Israelis; for the first time in the conflict, rockets fired from the Gaza Strip have fallen in the vicinity of the Israeli capital, Tel Aviv and the holy city of Jerusalem.
However, despite the fact that the Israelis and Palestinians are hopelessly bogged down in their perpetual conflict, changes have come to the Middle East.
This can be treated differently, but the events of the "Arab Spring" swirl in a rebellious storm of many established realities, and the Palestinians and the Israelis could not stay away from the vortex that shook the region.
Perhaps, as a result, their struggle will become even more bloody than before.
There are, however, reasons for the hope of a way out of this deadly impasse.
War without winners
At first glance, the current situation does not give reasons for optimism.
Even if the ceasefire, which was signed on 21 November, will be implemented, this week's clashes only strengthened the positions of the security forces on both sides.
The leaders of the Islamist Hamas movement, which came to power in the Gaza Strip in 2007, will say that they forced Israel to back down despite the losses they suffered.
Despite the fact that some of the group's leaders were destroyed, and 1.7 million inhabitants are blocked in one of the most densely populated and problematic corners of our planet, Israel failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is increasing its popularity in the West Bank, another Palestinian territory now controlled by the more moderate Fatah movement.
Moreover, Hamas leaders may well come to the conclusion that time is working for them.
As the influence of Islamist movements in the Arab world grows, Hamas has new powerful and wealthy friends.
Turkey's resurgent regional leader, which was once Israel's closest ally among Muslim countries, supported Hamas; Qatar, one of the richest and dynamic Gulf states, followed suit.
Hamas's celebrating the creation of an Islamist crescent around Israel - from Lebanon in the north, ruled by the Hezbollah paramilitary group, to Syria, in which increasingly pro-Islamic rebels are about to overthrow the power of Bashar alsad, and further to Jordan, where the king's authorities are threatened by Hamas's allies.
The most significant change in the balance of power in the region occurred on the southern borders of Israel, in the most populous and important Arab country, in Egypt, where under President Mohammed Morsi strengthened the influence of the Muslim Brotherhood.
Hosni Mubarak, who ruled Egypt for 30 years and was deposed in 2011, was a secular dictator who did not pay much attention to Hamas's support.
The Muslim Brotherhood, on the contrary, are an organization similar to Hamas, and their leaders are more prone to populism.
In future diplomatic arrangements, Hamas could become a significant player whose voice will not be able to drown even Israel and America.
At the same time, supporters of the "hard" line in Israel will come to the opposite conclusions.
In the military sense, Hamas was defeated.
The Israeli Iron Dome anti-missile system justified the cost of its creation and successfully destroyed many of the Hamas rockets launched.
Israeli citizens can sleep peacefully, at least for a while.
As for diplomacy, the US remained in its unaligned position; many European countries also blamed the start of the last round of violence against Hamas.
Another important factor is Israel's economic prosperity, especially under the government of Benjamin Netanyahu, which largely ignored the peace process.
Even though since 2004. Some 30 Israelis were killed by rockets fired from the Gaza Strip, and Israel has managed to minimize the problem of suicide bombers, in part by the wall that enters the West Bank - a large part of the unrecognized Palestinian State - and protects Jewish settlements, which continue to expand despite the illegality of such actions in terms of international law.
The position of Prime Minister Netanyahu, whose Likud party - in preparation for the January 22 elections - merged with even more aggressive conservatives under Avigdor Lieberman's leadership.
What's the point of indulging the Palestinians and giving them their own state?
If they give all the power in the West Bank, will they not launch rockets in the direction of Israel, as do their brethren in the Gaza Strip do?
It is better to keep them behind the wall and severely suppress any attempts to raise their heads.
Perhaps the supporters of the "hard" line will win; however, their calculations can be refuted by the Arab spring.
Despite the fact that the Islamists who come to power in Egypt and other countries do not have the warmest feelings for Israel, their priority will be internal problems.
The defense part of Israel's budget is greater than that of all of its Arab neighbors combined.
Unleashing a war with a regional superpower is unlikely to help Arab governments strengthen their own economies.
The pragmatism of the President of Egypt, Morsi, who worked with Barack Obama on a ceasefire, is a good sign and can mark the beginning of change.
Israel, to a no lesser extent, must take into account the long-term implications of its policies.
As the democratic change in the Arab countries advances, the Palestinians' right to self-determination is a time bomb that will explode sooner or later in the territories occupied by Israel, like the bus exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
The repression is already undermining the foundations of a democratic order in the Jewish state, and the demographic aspect - the growth of the Arab population - only exacerbates these problems.
The bloodshed operations, which are conducted every few years in the Gaza Strip to suppress the Hamas movement, have to pay the growing discontent of the international community.
Both sides need an external impulse.
The only solution remains to be called by sensible representatives on both sides, as well as most of the rest of the world and our newspaper: the formation of two states and Israel's concessions in exchange for security.
There is hope, not too impressive in the short term, the hope that a ceasefire will allow other countries to influence the parties to the conflict more effectively.
Egypt, which is high time to decide to cut arms supplies to the Gaza Strip, as well as Turkey and Qatar, have a more advantageous position than ever to convince Hamas to recognize the borders of the Jewish state adopted since 1967, taking into account the exchange of territories and the sharing of Jerusalem.
Other Arab countries should also make efforts to reconcile the Hamas and Fatah movements.
This would do more to create a Palestinian state than the upcoming UN vote, which could result in recognition of the virtual statehood of Palestine.
President Obama should play a role in putting Israel at the negotiating table.
During his first term, he never presented his own peace plan.
After returning to the White House, he still demonstrates the reluctance to connect to this problem.
This is a catastrophically short-sighted position.
The United States has a vital interest in stability in the Middle East.
This is possible only in the case of a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
In Australia, the law on unified packaging for cigarettes came into force.
Warnings about the dangers of smoking and the images of affected body parts of the body are contrasted on dull green boxes, the same for all brands of cigarettes.
The first Australian law on the same type of packaging of cigarettes and tobacco products came into force, replacing the logos and color design of different brands with the same box of dull-click color with creepy pictures of the affected body parts and images of children whose health is undermined by smoking their parents.
In addition to different pictures and inscriptions warning of the dangers of smoking, the only difference between the packs, introduced necessarily from this Saturday - the names of stamps that are printed in the same small print.
These are the most severe conditions in the world for packaging tobacco products.
The federal government of Australia says that the aim of this measure is to keep young people from smoking, depriving this harmful habit of buzzing.
The basis of this decision was the results of studies that showed that people who did not start smoking before the age of 26, in 99 out of 100 cases never become smokers.
"Obviously, even at the youngest age, children understand the meaning that tobacco companies are trying to convey with the help of packaging," Health Minister Tanya Plibersek explains, citing studies that, for example, the crown in the logo is associated in children with the idea of the princess.
Australia is one of the countries with the world's smallest share of smokers, so these changes will not affect the profits of transnational corporations, but other countries are already considering the possibility of such measures.
Representatives of the tobacco industry strongly opposed the enactment of this law.
Tobacco companies claim that this will only increase the black market share, which will sell cheap and affordable cigarettes.
"This law will lead to serious consequences, different from those that were conceived by its initiators," said Scott McIntyre, a spokesperson for British American Tobacco in Australia.
Manufacturers of counterfeit products from China and Indonesia will supply much more of these products for sale on the streets of Australia.
For someone, on the contrary, the new laws contribute to the growth of business.
Sandra Ha, of the small family-owned company Zico Import Pty Ltd, claims that the demand for cigarette cases and silicone cases hiding unpleasant pictures on the packaging has grown rapidly (almost from scratch) since two months ago, such as British American Tobacco, British Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Tobacco lost the case in the high court of Australia, where they tried to appeal the law.
According to Sandra Ha, Zico has already sold about six thousand products to wholesale enterprises and is waiting for a new batch.
It's a good business for us.
The potential hindrance to the effectiveness of such measures is, according to experts, the popularity of social networks among the part of the population to which these measures are aimed.
After the adoption in Australia of a number of laws that illegally advertise cigarettes and support for sports events, as well as prohibiting sellers from putting cigarettes in a prominent place, tobacco advertising has moved to the Internet.
The Australian government has banned local companies and websites from posting ads online, but it cannot restrict foreign sites.
