The heaviest profession in the world: miners from Kawah-Ijen
For four euros, Indonesian miners risk their lives and health, dragging 70 kilograms of sulfur to the top of the volcano on steep rocky paths
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others literally work in hell.
Among them is Anto Vijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn a living by mining sulfur in the Kawah Ijen volcano, located in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
Every day, Anto descends to the bottom of the crater, where sulfur gas rising from the depths of the Earth freezes when in contact with the air.
The breakdowns of huge pieces of sulfur, the total weight of which can reach 70 kg, he puts them in two bamboo baskets, sucks baskets on the shoulders and carries them up on a cliff rocky road.
To the top of the volcano, the height of which is 2.386 meters, is only 250 meters, but it takes more than 40 minutes for eminent loaders to climb the turtle, barely keeping the balance and gently groping the road so as not to stipble and fall off the cliff.
They know that one wrong move can cost them their lives, as happened with a French tourist who fell off the rocks of Kawah Ijen a few years ago.
Miners from Kawah-Ijen earn 5 euro cents for every kilogram of sulfur that is mined
Once at the top, they pave the way between tourists who photograph them, as if they were apes from the circus and, tiredly carrying heavy baskets, walk three kilometers to the scales that the mining company placed a little higher, at an altitude of 1,850 meters.
We are talking about the PT Kandy Ngrimbi, an enterprise that has been operating this volcano since 1960 and, better and not to say, its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 euros) for every kilogram of sulfur.
It then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 euro cents) to petrochemical plants, because this mineral is common in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to whiten sugar.
"Since the norm is the carrying of 70 kilograms, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each walker," explains Anto, who usually performs three daily carryings.
He spends three hours on each of them and at the end feels broken, but they allow him to accumulate 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) by the end of the day.
